element TargetAudiences
facets
Kind Value Annotation
enumeration Expert
documentation
Professionals on Biodiversity (researchers, decision makers, students of higher levels, etc.). By training and experience they have a good knowledge of scientific terminology and taxonomic and nomenclatural issues.
enumeration Knowledgeable
documentation
Public interest in the knowledge of living organisms but whose training and experience is not directly linked to knowledge of biodiversity, or to be enjoined, their training has not been directly related to biodiversity (professionals from other areas of knowledge, students, amateurs, etc.). Your level of interest is high but not usually use and know the terminology, taxonomy and scientific nomenclature.
enumeration General
documentation
General Public (anyone interested in living organisms). Persons interested on biodiversity, frequently or timely, but lack the training, expertise or basic knowledge on terminology, taxonomy or scientific nomenclature.
annotation
documentation
Repetitive concept where the target audiences are written one by one. (Predetermined list: 01. Expert (High). 02. Knowledgeable (Medium). 03. General (Low).

element DirectThreats
diagram
type DirectThreatsType
properties
content complex
children DirectThreatAtomized AncillaryData DirectThreatUnstructured
used by
complexType DemographyAndThreatType
annotation
documentation
Direct threats are the proximate human activities or processes that have caused, are causing, or may cause the destruction, degradation, and/or impairment of biodiversity targets (e.g., unsustainable fishing or logging). Direct threats are synonymous with sources of stress and proximate pressures. Threats can be past (historical), ongoing, and/or likely to occur in the future.
source <xs:element name="DirectThreats" type="DirectThreatsType">
  <xs:annotation>
    <xs:documentation>Direct threats are the proximate human activities or processes that have caused, are causing, or may cause the destruction, degradation, and/or impairment of biodiversity targets (e.g., unsustainable fishing or logging). Direct threats are synonymous with sources of stress and proximate pressures. Threats can be past (historical), ongoing, and/or likely to occur in the future.</xs:documentation>
  </xs:annotation>
</xs:element>

element IdentificationKeys
diagram
properties
content complex
children Keys AncillaryData
used by
complexType TaxonomicalDescriptionType
annotation
documentation
Tool for the identification of organisms, comprising a series of steps, each of which represents a question about one or more characters of the organism. Each step offers multiple alternatives, choosing one of them will lead us to the next step until ending, finally, in the name of the organism. Most printed keys have only two alternatives, so called dichotomous keys.                                                      A taxon includes a key or an identification of key  in the subordinate taxons.
For example:
If we are in a register of a genre, this register would include the keys of the species that this register includes, and if it´s one specie, then it would include the key of the infraspecific rank (For plants: subspecies, variety forms)
